body:
> dynamic than Java in that it allows you to define methods with the same name as an imported method as long as you have different types

compile error in java:

``` java
import static java.lang.String.format;

public class Dummy {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(format("String")); // compile error
        System.out.println(new Dummy().format(Integer.valueOf(1)));
    }

    public String format(Integer i) {
        return i.toString();
    }
}
```

valid groovy:

``` groovy
import static java.lang.String.format

class Dummy {
    static void main(String[] args) {
        println(format("String"))
        println(new Dummy().format(Integer.valueOf(1)))
    }

    String format(Integer i) {
        return i.toString()
    }
}
```

> How can we fix it in one place, outside of the original class, without changing all the code thats using it? Groovy has an elegant solution to this problem.
> Is this example valid? I mean the imports will need to be changed. Correct?

I agree the example is not very helpful. As you said the imports will need to be changed when the class is not defined in the same file. It would be better to change the section with an import alias e.g using `java.util.Date` and `java.sql.Date as SQLDate` or something similar.
